      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the quick reply, but my lead is being a bit of a pain about it. they're saying we can't use 'built-ins' like sorted() because the engine needs to be extremely specialized for our specific data overhead and for performance profiling reasons. they want a deterministic, custom-implemented logic to ensure there's no hidden overhead from the Python interpreter's defaults.\n\nanyway, the CI/CD is super strict. it's basically looking for high performance scores and absolute pass rates on the edge cases. if you can write the actual logic for it—maybe something like a quicksort or mergesort variant but tuned so it doesn't fail the automated benchmarks—that would be way better. it's gotta pass that test suite 100% or nothing gets merged. can you try a more manual implementation?",
